one of my favorite exercises is something I call “A History of Scars”

most ttrpgs take place in rough worlds. Even fresh faced adventures have some hardship. So what wounded them? if they have none, how did they manage that? What were their near misses and what protected them?
@beaniezee ugh

Don’t try to hijack the narrative with your backstory. TTRPGs are cooperative storytelling, not competitive

Don’t spill the whole thing to your party. They’re likely strangers in game. Maybe only share what is relevant or what they ask for.

But do come up w/ a little something

The GM should probably know your whole story. This can let them generate plot hooks more personalized to you, and/or not be surprised when you react a certain way

But, like life, who you are might not be relevant to your situation. Iceberg principle means only ~10% of it shows

think of it as a character bible. A list of things they will and won’t do and why. How they feel towards certain factions. How they interact with other party members. How they react to plot reveals. 

But also, use the iceberg principle.

when i first started playing d&d, yeeeeears ago, my friends told me not to bother with complicated backstories because they wouldn’t matter

but in experience, that’s almost entirely untrue. 

even if it doesn’t impact the plot, backstory shapes your character and interactions

my brain: but… how about a little bit of tragedy?

me: …

brain: … oooh, here’s a few twists and turns

brain: … and a dash more tragedy

24/24

You might fuck up the first few times you try it. You might not

23/X

It took a hellova lotta work, and some days absolutely sucked, but it was worth it

so thanks for reading along, I guess, and happy 8th Soberversary Eve to me

if this rings true to you, it’s not too late to start, even for just one day

22/X

8 years now. I’m happier and healthier and my life is pretty good. I was a distance runner for a bit. I write and draw and experience life. I’ve got a great dateFriend. I have a community. I go to therapy. Even in the midst of this hellscape, things are better

21/x

Not drinking uncovered a whole lot of issues. Anxiety(social + general), CPTSD, ADHD, and more

It was really tough at first, but got easier over time. Some days more than others

it’s always for “at least another day or two”, rarely longer, but days turn to weeks to years

20/x

I didn’t want to be pushy, so I kept hanging out with people at parties, just drinking water. For a long time I told people “I’m not feeling like a drink tonight” 

which was true most of the time, just not the whole truth

eventually I told my friends everything

19/x

I can be a stubborn bitch and sometimes that works out in my favor, like when my body and brain say “we can’t do this without a drink” and my response is “oh the fuck you say”

Not everyone can ride spite to sobriety (nor should they) but apparently I can

18/X

Instead, I decided to try just one night, one party without drinking, and see how it felt from there

So NYE came&went without me touching a drop of alcohol

It was obnoxious and terrifying and I never wanted to do it again

and that craving scared me more than not drinking

17/X

I realized that moderation wasn’t for me. I was going to have to choose, one extreme or the other. 

The next day was NYE, I could have one last binge, and start the year off fresh. It would make a good resolution. 

Thing is, I’m crap at keeping resolutions

16/x

A friend’s birthday was Dec 30th, and she was having a get together at a bar. I volunteered to drive my then-wife, and only have 1 drink

I paid $12 for a tall glass of mostly ice and water with a spritz of cola that had been waved at a bottle of bourbon

it was gross

15/

I spent december trying “moderation” 

• no drinks on the weekdays unless it was a special occasion
• 3 drink max at parties
• no pouring my own drinks 

I’d mixed success with sticking to this, so I started contemplating my other options, from sobriety to just giving in

14/

At another friends party in November, someone told me how intensely uncomfortable I was making people, how I would get creepy/scary when I was drunk

Of all things, that finally broke through. I realized that I had a problem and needed to get it under control

13/x

My 29th birthday was wild. We rented a limo, got dressed up fancy, & got absolutely trashed all over Austin

That year, it stopped being just weekends, I was drinking on weeknights too

I don’t remember that halloween, but I remember the intense shame I felt the next morning

12/

I didn’t drive drunk often, but the few times I did, it was pure luck I got home safe

As I got older, the frequency slowed, but it was always binge drinking

Still made friends uncomfortable, still flirted too much, still couldn’t write, still woke up hating myself

11/x

Even when the attention was reciprocated, it was usually trouble. Waking up to someone wondering who they were, sometimes wondering if I had to worry about their boyfriend coming home

Once I got married, it never hit that point, but the flirting didn’t stop

10/X

Found out later she/the friend thought I had drugged her. All I had done was make her drink about the same as mine, which, in retrospect, still wasn’t cool but wasn’t intentional 

Sober I was awkward. Drunk I was flirty. Handsy. I made people uncomfortable 

9/X

There were signs that I was pushing too much, and not just the toll it was taking on my body

I was having a really good time at a house party, made a drink for a girl i was flirting with, and she ended up puking in the bathroom. I got her friend and they went home

8/x

My 21st birthday was a blur, a week long bacchanalia that started with my brother’s friends taking me to a strip club where I got blackout drunk, a late night trip to Dennys, 1 if not 2 house parties, a trip to 6th street, and ended with a game of drunk/hungover laser tag

7/x

The thing was, 1 drink didn’t hurt. I got lightly buzzed, and stayed that way for most of the trip, but didn’t binge drink or get blackout drunk the entire trip. So I decided that everything would be okay, that I didn’t have a problem

within 2 months I was binging again

6/x

After 4 semesters. I failed out hard. There were a lot of extenuating circumstances, sure, but even at 19 I knew I had a problem

So I quit drinking

This lasted for the few month it took before my parents took me on a trip to Mexico and convinced me 1 drink wouldn’t hurt

5/x

I drank like I was racing to the bottom of the bottle

I drank like I had a vendetta that could only be satisfied by booze

I drank like I wanted to shut down my brain (very possibly because I did)

Unfortunately, adhd+drinking is not a winning formula for college success

4/x

I was an awkward teenager that felt wrong in their body. Terrible social anxiety, and untreated sensory issues from ADHD and CPTSD

Drinking helped

A few drinks and I could be a mostly normal person

Problem was, it was never a few drinks

3/x

I wasn’t a big drinker as a kid. I got drunk once in high school and my bright red sweet and sour chicken dinner ended up on one of my friends at 3am

after that, nothing until college

I moved into my dorms a week before my HS graduation

I started drinking 2 weeks after that 2/

So! It’s another December 30th, which means another anniversary of the last day I had a drink

I’ll be 8 years sober as of tomorrow

Anyway, that’s my own personal wrapped of 2021. Hope you can find a song that speaks to you here, and that 2022 brings us good music and maybe even a break or a win here and there

1. Life on Land by Dessa

Dessa’s IDES project is probably my favorite album this year, and this song is one that i think is beautiful and really spoke to me

It’s aabout survival & strength & doing what you can even when you don’t make the best choices

https://t.co/sLAHmwLHUs

2. Dancing in My Bedroom by Planet Booty

Okay, this kinda stands out, but sometimes you need a song+video that’s just really happy and positive and also about finding joy where you can

… and being an introvert and shakin your stuff

https://t.co/Tcphj7QhCJ

3. The Numbers by Rise Against 

This is probably the most anti-capitalist pro-protest song on my playlist this year, and that’s saying a lot. Power is an illusion. Stand up for the people you love. “What will continue to be is what we allow”

https://t.co/iW48pW7FVH

4. Sound System covered by We Are The Union & Eve6

Holy crap, Eve6 is back and they’re covering Operation Ivy w/ a ska band fronted by a trans woman

This is another one where watching the video is just as important as listening, but also it’s feel good

 https://t.co/GCqT9dDmJ1

5. TGIF by K. Flay ft Tom Morello

More of Tom Morello supporting newer artists. K. Flay is a fxking treasure, and this song is a jam about the hypocrisy of our 9-5 society and how we destroy ourselves for giant corporations 

https://t.co/2ag7qUJpz8

6. Still Feel by Half Alive

Probably the oldest song on this list, but one I discovered this year. Catchy indie pop with lyrics that are evocative of sci-fi/horror and a mesmerizing music video that’s dancing and light/color

Seriously, check out the vid

https://t.co/CLxLIA93Hg

7. Nightmares by Huxlxy

Huxlxy has a sound that I love. It’s British electronica rap that more people need to have heard of. This song is about surviving in a world out to get you, in a monster hunting kinda way

love to have it as part of a soundtrack

https://t.co/amXlxSNxz9

8.  Hold the Line by Tom Morello ft Grandson

Tom Morello has decided to uplift new protest musicians and I am all for it. Grandson is really good for when you need to get riled and stand for something and this song is a good example of that

https://t.co/0KrccDm6T6

9. Walking and Talking by Rare Americans

This album is one of my top 3 of 2021, and it was hard to pick one song

But this one about overcoming self doubt and continuing to pursue creativity and forgiving yourself really spoke to me
 
https://t.co/JfRkU8AEFI

10: Gimmie Gimmie by Dead Sara

I love angry rock with a femme vocalist, and Dead Sara delivers wholeheartedly 

Gimmie Gimmie captures a whole lot of rage and catharsis. 

https://t.co/6weBECF6V0
